Two minutes.
(BRAKES SCREECH)

246
00:12:11,357 --> 00:12:12,483
(GROANING)

247
00:12:12,901 --> 00:12:14,319
Make sure
you kill 'em both!

248
00:12:23,286 --> 00:12:26,080
I got two handguns,
one automatic.

249
00:12:30,126 --> 00:12:31,336
(TIRES SCREECHING)

250
00:12:38,760 --> 00:12:41,012
We gotta get out of here.
I'm gonna take the automatic.

251
00:12:41,179 --> 00:12:42,472
You sure about this?

252
00:12:54,525 --> 00:12:56,778
(GUNS FIRING)

253
00:13:04,827 --> 00:13:05,828
You ready?

254
00:13:06,120 --> 00:13:07,121
Move.

255
00:13:28,685 --> 00:13:29,852
(GRUNTING)

256
00:13:37,735 --> 00:13:38,903
(GROANS)

257
00:13:47,662 --> 00:13:48,830
Lewis!

258
00:13:49,747 --> 00:13:50,873
Lewis!

259
00:13:53,751 --> 00:13:57,422
Officer down!
Officer down, 331 Hamilton.

260
00:13:57,588 --> 00:13:59,048
This is Detective Alex Murphy

261
00:13:59,132 --> 00:14:01,050
in need of immediate
medical assistance.

262
00:14:01,217 --> 00:14:03,219
331 Hamilton Road.

263
00:14:04,220 --> 00:14:05,263
Jack.

264
00:14:06,264 --> 00:14:09,225
Jack, come on.
Jack. Can you hear me?

265
00:14:09,767 --> 00:14:11,728
Jack. Stay with me.

266
00:14:12,687 --> 00:14:13,771
Jack.

267
00:14:14,355 --> 00:14:17,608
KAREN: <i>Alex, you don't
do something like this</i>

268
00:14:17,775 --> 00:14:19,444
unless you bring it
to me first.

269
00:14:19,610 --> 00:14:20,945
Vallon's connected.

270
00:14:21,112 --> 00:14:24,907
I'm warning you,
don't make any more moves
until I vet this.

271
00:14:25,074 --> 00:14:26,784
If officers are
supplying him with guns...

272
00:14:26,868 --> 00:14:28,953
That's up to IAD.

273
00:14:29,412 --> 00:14:30,913
I'll handle it.

274
00:14:36,586 --> 00:14:41,257
I don't care how
sophisticated these
machines are, Mr. Sellars.

275
00:14:41,466 --> 00:14:45,970
A machine does not know
what it feels like
to be human.

276
00:14:46,137 --> 00:14:48,514
It can't understand
the value of human life.

277
00:14:48,598 --> 00:14:50,099
Why should it be
allowed to take one?

278
00:14:50,183 --> 00:14:51,184
(APPLAUSE)

279
00:14:51,309 --> 00:14:54,687
To legislate
over life and death,

280
00:14:54,771 --> 00:14:58,566
we need people
who understand
right from wrong.

281
00:14:58,900 --> 00:15:00,985
What do your machines feel?

282
00:15:01,152 --> 00:15:04,614
Well, they feel no anger.
They feel no prejudice.

283
00:15:04,781 --> 00:15:09,327
They feel no fatigue,
which makes them ideal
for law enforcement.

284
00:15:10,328 --> 00:15:13,498
Putting these machines
on the streets

285
00:15:13,664 --> 00:15:16,667
will save countless
American lives.

286
00:15:16,834 --> 00:15:18,669
DREYFUS: You're evading
the question.
No, I'm not.

287
00:15:18,836 --> 00:15:19,879
DREYFUS: Yes,
you're evading the question.

288
00:15:19,962 --> 00:15:23,424
I asked what do
these machines feel?

289
00:15:23,591 --> 00:15:26,427
If one of them
killed a child,

290
00:15:27,512 --> 00:15:28,971
what would it feel?

291
00:15:29,055 --> 00:15:30,306
(SIGHS)

292
00:15:32,600 --> 00:15:34,477
Nothing.
And that's the problem.

293
00:15:34,644 --> 00:15:39,941
That's why 72% of Americans
will not stand for
a robot pulling the trigger.

294
00:15:40,024 --> 00:15:41,859
(APPLAUSE)

295
00:15:46,781 --> 00:15:50,910
POPE: America is the world's
most valuable market,
and we can't touch it.

296
00:15:51,202 --> 00:15:56,499
With a domestic expansion,
we'd clear $600 billion
per annum.

297
00:15:56,666 --> 00:16:01,546
In other words, every second
that law is in existence,
we are hemorrhaging money.

298
00:16:01,712 --> 00:16:02,713
What do you
want me to do?

299
00:16:02,880 --> 00:16:06,217
We've thrown cash at senators
at both sides of the aisle.
Nobody's budging.

300
00:16:06,384 --> 00:16:08,302
They don't want
to vote against
their constituents.

301
00:16:08,469 --> 00:16:11,514
So unless
we sway public opinion,
the battle's lost.

302
00:16:11,681 --> 00:16:13,641
Now, to that effect,

303
00:16:13,808 --> 00:16:18,062
my team have come up with
a pretty aggressive
new campaign.

304
00:16:18,229 --> 00:16:20,731
Wow factor
off-the-charts.

305
00:16:20,898 --> 00:16:23,734
We need to give Americans
a product they can love.

306
00:16:24,068 --> 00:16:25,736
A figure
they can rally behind.

307
00:16:25,903 --> 00:16:28,906
Sir, I have
dissected this bill.
There are no loopholes.

308
00:16:29,073 --> 00:16:30,741
We can't put a machine
on the streets.

309
00:16:30,825 --> 00:16:32,034
SELLARS: Forget machines.

310
00:16:32,201 --> 00:16:33,578
You saw the polls.

311
00:16:34,036 --> 00:16:36,247
Americans don't
want a machine.

312
00:16:37,498 --> 00:16:39,083
They want

313
00:16:39,167 --> 00:16:41,919
a product
with a conscience.

314
00:16:42,545 --> 00:16:44,505
They want

315
00:16:44,589 --> 00:16:47,466
something that knows

316
00:16:48,509 --> 00:16:51,012
what it feels like

317
00:16:51,095 --> 00:16:52,555
to be human.

318
00:16:59,103 --> 00:17:01,439
We're gonna put a man
inside a machine.

319
00:17:05,234 --> 00:17:09,071
DR. NORTON: You're not you
because of your legs,
your arms, your hands.

320
00:17:09,155 --> 00:17:10,823
You're you because
of your brain.

321
00:17:10,907 --> 00:17:15,328
It's your brain's capacity
to process information
that makes you who you are.

322
00:17:16,704 --> 00:17:20,958
Relax, and just do
what you've always done.

323
00:17:22,251 --> 00:17:23,461
(SIGHS)

324
00:17:24,754 --> 00:17:26,589
I've never played
with these.

325
00:17:26,797 --> 00:17:31,093
The music doesn't come
from your fingers, Michael,
it comes from your mind.

326
00:17:31,260 --> 00:17:33,221
All you have to do
is let it out.

327
00:17:34,180 --> 00:17:35,306
Please.

328
00:17:47,318 --> 00:17:48,861
(PLAYING
<i>CONCIERTO DE ARANJUEZ)</i>

329
00:18:06,170 --> 00:18:07,630
Oh, my God.

330
00:18:08,256 --> 00:18:09,507
(CHUCKLING)

331
00:18:11,968 --> 00:18:13,552
No, it's okay. Easy.

332
00:18:14,470 --> 00:18:15,596
(PLAYS OFF-KEY)

333
00:18:15,680 --> 00:18:18,307
His emotions are peaking.
The readings are
getting clouded.

334
00:18:18,641 --> 00:18:19,642
DR. NORTON: It's okay.

335
00:18:20,268 --> 00:18:22,645
Relax. If you get
too emotional,

336
00:18:22,728 --> 00:18:24,605
it'll change the chemistry
in your brain.

337
00:18:24,772 --> 00:18:26,524
It'll throw the system out.

338
00:18:29,610 --> 00:18:32,113
You're doing great.
Come on.

339
00:18:34,699 --> 00:18:36,450
(CONTINUES PLAYING
<i>CONCIERTO DE ARANJUEZ)</i>

340
00:18:46,794 --> 00:18:48,713
I need emotion to play.

341
00:18:49,547 --> 00:18:51,674
SELLARS:
<i>Concierto de Aranjuez,</i>
second movement.

342
00:18:53,050 --> 00:18:54,552
Beautiful piece.

343
00:18:54,635 --> 00:18:57,430
Dennett, when you
have a moment. Thank you.

344
00:18:57,680 --> 00:19:00,683
Now, we agreed on this
a long time ago, Raymond.

345
00:19:00,766 --> 00:19:04,478
I wouldn't be asked
to develop
combat applications.

346
00:19:04,645 --> 00:19:07,815
My work here
is driven by
its own questions.

347
00:19:07,898 --> 00:19:11,444
And your work is brilliant.
But your ideas are
being underutilized.

348
00:19:11,527 --> 00:19:14,280
Look, I think
I found a way

349
00:19:14,363 --> 00:19:18,117
to put real revenue stream
behind your research

350
00:19:18,784 --> 00:19:21,871
and save thousands
of lives in the process.

351
00:19:34,717 --> 00:19:36,093
VALLON: You're not
keeping up your end,

352
00:19:36,177 --> 00:19:37,511
leaving me exposed
like that.

353
00:19:37,678 --> 00:19:39,472
Detective Murphy's
just a little impulsive.

354
00:19:39,638 --> 00:19:40,723
So put him
on the payroll.

355
00:19:40,806 --> 00:19:41,807
Why are we talkin'
about this?

356
00:19:41,974 --> 00:19:43,517
It won't work. And now that
his partner got hit,

357
00:19:43,601 --> 00:19:45,519
he's never gonna let it go.

358
00:19:45,686 --> 00:19:47,563
What is that?
Lewis' hospital.

359
00:19:47,730 --> 00:19:49,023
Alex is dropping by
this afternoon,

360
00:19:49,106 --> 00:19:51,192
in case you want
to send flowers.

361
00:19:53,944 --> 00:19:55,196
(SCOFFS)

362
00:19:55,488 --> 00:19:56,614
Yeah.

363
00:19:56,781 --> 00:19:58,157
I kill a cop,

364
00:19:58,240 --> 00:19:59,909
lookin' over my shoulder
the rest of my life.

365
00:19:59,992 --> 00:20:01,327
That's not good
for business.

366
00:20:02,119 --> 00:20:04,413
Who do you think's
gonna be investigating you?

367
00:20:10,586 --> 00:20:12,922
I'm gonna go hard
after Lake and Daniels.

368
00:20:15,132 --> 00:20:17,635
I'm gonna
have 'em in bracelets
within a month, man.

369
00:20:19,470 --> 00:20:21,097
MARCUS: Hey, Vallon,
I'm walking up right now.

370
00:20:22,264 --> 00:20:23,682
Cameras off?

371
00:20:25,059 --> 00:20:26,060
Clear.

372
00:20:27,353 --> 00:20:30,940
MURPHY: <i>You were right.
We should've had backup.</i>

373
00:20:31,107 --> 00:20:32,483
<i>I'm sorry.</i>

374
00:20:35,986 --> 00:20:37,822
You're not really sleeping,
are ya?

375
00:20:38,656 --> 00:20:40,074
(CHUCKLES)

376
00:20:40,449 --> 00:20:41,575
Asshole.

377
00:20:43,953 --> 00:20:48,749
Sergeant Thomas Ryan, NYPD.
Paralyzed from the waist down.

378
00:20:49,333 --> 00:20:53,212
He has let himself
go a little since
the accident.

379
00:20:53,379 --> 00:20:54,505
SELLARS: Pass.

380
00:20:54,672 --> 00:20:56,132
Yeah. Yeah, fair enough.

381
00:20:56,674 --> 00:20:59,135
Officer Alfred Miller,
Denver.

382
00:20:59,635 --> 00:21:02,847
"Severe Cerebellar..."

383
00:21:02,930 --> 00:21:04,515
Cerebellar ataxia.

384
00:21:04,765 --> 00:21:06,267
That's why you're
the doctor, Doctor.

385
00:21:06,851 --> 00:21:10,521
He scored through the roof
with our urban demos.

386
00:21:10,604 --> 00:21:12,189
Let's keep this one
in mind. I like this guy.

387
00:21:12,440 --> 00:21:15,151
Very good, sir.
I saved the best for last.

388
00:21:16,694 --> 00:21:20,781
I give you
Sergeant Jack Freeman,
masculinity incarnate.

389
00:21:20,865 --> 00:21:23,242
Led Pittsburgh SWAT
for five years,

390
00:21:23,325 --> 00:21:25,411
now confined
to a wheelchair.

391
00:21:27,830 --> 00:21:29,957
I think I can
see the appeal.

392
00:21:30,040 --> 00:21:31,041
DR. NORTON: No.

393
00:21:31,125 --> 00:21:33,002
(SIGHS) What? Why?

394
00:21:33,169 --> 00:21:36,088
Well, check
the psych evaluation.
He's far too unstable.

395
00:21:36,255 --> 00:21:38,048
He's trying to say
that he has a temper.

396
00:21:38,340 --> 00:21:40,718
DR. NORTON: Have you
any idea what we'd be
putting him through?

397
00:21:40,885 --> 00:21:44,138
The psychological strain
requires someone
emotionally balanced.

398
00:21:44,305 --> 00:21:46,348
We have to be scientific.

399
00:21:46,515 --> 00:21:49,226
I mean, we're not selling
a soft drink here, are we?

400
00:21:49,393 --> 00:21:52,104
He's right. Okay.
Keep looking.

401
00:21:54,023 --> 00:21:56,942
CLARA: David, what did I say?
Not until you're finished.

402
00:21:57,109 --> 00:21:59,111
Hey, guys.
Hi, Dad.

403
00:21:59,487 --> 00:22:02,072
Hey.
Hey, little monkey.

404
00:22:06,327 --> 00:22:07,536
How's the game, buddy?

405
00:22:07,703 --> 00:22:10,581
Damon got ejected,
but we got
a two-man advantage.

406
00:22:10,748 --> 00:22:13,584
Oh, yeah?
That's fantastic.

407
00:22:13,667 --> 00:22:15,211
Hey, D, why don't
you head upstairs

408
00:22:15,294 --> 00:22:16,962
and start getting ready
for bed.

409
00:22:17,213 --> 00:22:18,797
But he just got home.

410
00:22:19,423 --> 00:22:20,883
I'll be up in a second.

411
00:22:20,966 --> 00:22:23,427
Tuck you in, okay?
All right?

412
00:22:23,511 --> 00:22:24,595
(GRUNTS)

413
00:22:27,264 --> 00:22:29,183
Now give your mom a kiss.
Good night, baby.

414
00:22:29,350 --> 00:22:30,559
Too slow, boy.

415
00:22:32,603 --> 00:22:34,146
You're just too slow.

416
00:22:42,071 --> 00:22:43,239
How's Jack holding up?

417
00:22:43,405 --> 00:22:45,866
They said a week
till he's back on his feet.

418
00:22:46,742 --> 00:22:47,701
It's my fault.

419
00:22:47,785 --> 00:22:49,161
We shouldn't even
have been there.

420
00:22:51,830 --> 00:22:52,831
Here.

421
00:23:53,851 --> 00:23:55,561
(CAR ALARM BLARING
IN DISTANCE)

422
00:23:57,146 --> 00:23:58,939
Oh, shit, I thought
I fixed that.

423
00:23:59,106 --> 00:24:00,399
It'll stop.

424
00:24:03,777 --> 00:24:05,154
(MOANING SOFTLY)

425
00:24:06,697 --> 00:24:08,449
It's gonna
wake up David.

426
00:24:11,452 --> 00:24:13,078
(ALARM CONTINUES BLARING)

427
00:24:17,041 --> 00:24:18,375
(CLICKING)

428
00:24:28,302 --> 00:24:29,386
(CLICKS)

429
00:24:32,973 --> 00:24:34,391
(UNLOCKS CAR)

430
00:24:52,201 --> 00:24:56,705
DR. NORTON: <i>He suffered</i>
<i>4th degree burns</i>
<i>over 80% of his body.</i>

431
00:24:57,289 --> 00:24:59,708
<i>Lower spine
has been severed.</i>

432
00:25:00,668 --> 00:25:02,586
<i>If he survives,</i>

433
00:25:03,379 --> 00:25:07,257
he'll be paralyzed
from the waist down
and confined to a wheelchair.

434
00:25:10,010 --> 00:25:11,720
Mrs. Murphy,

435
00:25:13,472 --> 00:25:15,808
we don't have to do this.

436
00:25:17,142 --> 00:25:20,187
I need to know everything
before I make a decision.

437
00:25:21,271 --> 00:25:22,606
(SIGHS)

438
00:25:23,482 --> 00:25:24,942
Please continue.

439
00:25:25,943 --> 00:25:28,070
Vestibulocochlear,

440
00:25:28,153 --> 00:25:31,240
optical nerves have
been critically damaged.

441
00:25:32,282 --> 00:25:34,410
He'll be blind in one eye.

442
00:25:35,035 --> 00:25:36,495
Most likely deaf.

443
00:25:37,538 --> 00:25:39,707
Frankly, Dr. Norton
and the Omni Foundation

444
00:25:39,790 --> 00:25:41,291
are the leaders
in this field.

445
00:25:41,458 --> 00:25:45,045
In my opinion,
this is the only chance
your husband has.

446
00:25:45,212 --> 00:25:47,589
I'd seriously
consider their offer.

447
00:25:50,384 --> 00:25:51,677
I'm sorry, Doctor.

448
00:25:53,262 --> 00:25:54,680
I need time to think.

449
00:25:54,847 --> 00:25:58,767
I'm afraid,
Mrs. Murphy, time is
one thing you don't have.

450
00:26:02,813 --> 00:26:05,649
You say you can save him,
but what does that mean?

451
00:26:08,902 --> 00:26:10,863
What kind of life
will he have?

452
00:26:13,741 --> 00:26:15,075
(<i>FLY ME TO THE MOON</i> PLAYING)

453
00:26:20,497 --> 00:26:22,750
FRANK SINATRA: (SINGING)
<i>Fly me to the moon</i>

454
00:26:23,417 --> 00:26:27,129
<i>Let me play
among the stars</i>

455
00:26:27,838 --> 00:26:30,215
Thanks.
Thanks, buddy.

456
00:26:30,382 --> 00:26:32,176
You know she's gonna
make me dance again.

457
00:26:32,301 --> 00:26:34,011
Now that I've gotta see.

458
00:26:34,178 --> 00:26:35,179
You don't want
to see that.

459
00:26:35,262 --> 00:26:36,930
Here she comes now.

460
00:26:37,097 --> 00:26:38,223
Hold on to that.

461
00:26:38,307 --> 00:26:39,558
Get out there, partner.

462
00:26:41,101 --> 00:26:42,853
Every time.

463
00:26:46,690 --> 00:26:47,775
LEWIS: Get her, boy.

464
00:26:47,900 --> 00:26:49,693
(BOTH CHUCKLING)

465
00:26:52,821 --> 00:26:55,324
<i>Fill my heart with song</i>

466
00:26:55,407 --> 00:26:59,745
<i>And let me sing forever more</i>

467
00:27:00,788 --> 00:27:03,999
<i>You are all I long for</i>

468
00:27:04,082 --> 00:27:06,168
<i>All I worship...</i>

469
00:27:06,251 --> 00:27:08,212
KIM: Subject is
still dreaming.

470
00:27:08,295 --> 00:27:09,463
(CONTINUES SINGING)

471
00:27:09,546 --> 00:27:11,131
He's retrieving memories,

472
00:27:11,215 --> 00:27:14,635
trying to make sense
of sensorial stimulation
package 37.

473
00:27:15,636 --> 00:27:17,179
Perfect, Kim.

474
00:27:18,680 --> 00:27:20,682
Let's reconnect the spine.

475
00:27:21,683 --> 00:27:23,185
Time to wake him up.

476
00:27:26,855 --> 00:27:29,817
<i>Fill my heart with song</i>

477
00:27:29,900 --> 00:27:33,487
<i>Let me sing forever more</i>

478
00:27:34,822 --> 00:27:37,991
<i>You are all I long for</i>

479
00:27:38,075 --> 00:27:42,412
<i>All I worship and adore</i>

480
00:27:42,996 --> 00:27:45,082
<i>In other words</i>

481
00:27:45,582 --> 00:27:49,586
<i>Please be true</i>

482
00:27:49,670 --> 00:27:51,213
Excuse me?

483
00:27:51,839 --> 00:27:53,423
What are you doing here?

484
00:27:53,715 --> 00:27:55,175
Baby, where you going?

485
00:27:55,259 --> 00:27:58,554
<i>In other words</i>

486
00:27:58,637 --> 00:27:59,763
Lewis.

487
00:28:00,013 --> 00:28:03,725
<i>I love</i>

488
00:28:07,396 --> 00:28:08,730
<i>You</i>

489
00:28:10,440 --> 00:28:13,652
Subject regaining
cognitive functions.

490
00:28:15,529 --> 00:28:16,822
What's happening?

491
00:28:19,241 --> 00:28:20,242
Where am I?

492
00:28:20,409 --> 00:28:24,913
You were
in an explosion, Alex.
You're in a hospital.

493
00:28:24,997 --> 00:28:26,081
(STAMMERING)

494
00:28:27,332 --> 00:28:29,835
Where's Clara? My wife.
Where's my wife?

495
